{{Calculus/Top Nav|Volume|Arc length}}
In this section we cover '''solids of revolution''' and how to calculate their volume. A solid of revolution is a solid formed by revolving a 2-dimensional region around an axis. For example, revolving the semi-circular region bounded by the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=\sqrt{1-x^2}</math>{{nowrap end}} and the line {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}} around the <math>x</math>-axis produces a sphere. There are two main methods of calculating the volume of a solid of revolution using calculus: the disk method and the shell method.
==Disk Method== [[Image:Generating fx disk method.svg|thumb|397px|right|Figure 1: A solid of revolution is generated by revolving this region around the x-axis.]] [[Image:Approx generating fx disk method.svg|thumb|397px|right|Figure 2: Approximation to the generating region in Figure 1.]] Consider the solid formed by revolving the region bounded by the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=f(x)</math>{{nowrap end}}, which is continuous on {{nowrap begin}}<math>[a,b]</math>{{nowrap end}}, and the lines {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=a</math>{{nowrap end}}, {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=b</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}} around the <math>x</math>-axis. We could imagine approximating the volume by approximating <math>f(x)</math> with the stepwise function <math>g(x)</math> shown in [[:File:Approx generating fx disk method.svg|{{nowrap begin}}figure 2{{nowrap end}}]], which uses a right-handed approximation to the function. Now when the region is revolved, the region under each step sweeps out a cylinder, whose volume we know how to calculate, i.e. :<math>V_{cylinder}=\pi r^2 h</math> , where <math>r</math> is the radius of the cylinder and <math>h</math> is the cylinder's height. This process is reminiscent of the Riemann process we used to calculate areas earlier. Let's try to write the volume as a Riemann sum and from that equate the volume to an integral by taking the limit as the subdivisions get infinitely small.
Consider the volume of one of the cylinders in the approximation, say the <math>k</math>-th one from the left. The cylinder's radius is the height of the step function, and the thickness is the length of the subdivision. With <math>n</math> subdivisions and a length of <math>b-a</math> for the total length of the region, each subdivision has width :<math>\Delta x=\frac{b-a}{n}</math> Since we are using a right-handed approximation, the <math>k</math>-th sample point will be :<math>x_k=k\Delta x</math> So the volume of the <math>k</math>-th cylinder is :<math>V_k=\pi f(x_k)^2\Delta x</math> Summing all of the cylinders in the region from <math>a</math> to <math>b</math>, we have :<math>V_{approx}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\pi f(x_k)^2\Delta x</math> Taking the limit as <math>n</math> approaches infinity gives us the the exact volume :<math>V=\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\pi f(x_k)^2\Delta x</math> , which is equivalent to the integral :<math>V=\int_a^b \pi f(x)^2 dx</math>
{{ExampleRobox|title=Example: Volume of a Sphere}} Let's calculate the volume of a sphere using the disk method. Our generating region will be the region bounded by the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>f(x)=\sqrt{r^2-x^2}</math>{{nowrap end}} and the line {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}}. Our limits of integration will be the <math>x</math>-values where the curve intersects the line {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}}, namely, {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=\pm r</math>{{nowrap end}}. We have :<math>\begin{align}V_{sphere}&=\int_{-r}^r \pi(r^2-x^2)dx\\ &=\pi(\int_{-r}^r r^2 dx-\int_{-r}^r x^2 dx)\\ &=\pi(r^2 x\bigr|_{-r}^r - \frac{x^3}{3}\biggr|_{-r}^r)\\ &=\pi(r^2 (r-(-r)) - (\frac{r^3}{3}-\frac{(-r)^3}{3})\\ &=\pi(2r^3-\frac{2r^3}{3})\\ &=\pi\frac{6r^3-2r^3}{3}\\ &=\frac{4\pi r^3}{3} \end{align}</math> {{Robox/Close}}
===Exercises=== {{question-answer|question=1. Calculate the volume of the cone with radius <math>R</math> and height <math>h</math> which is generated by the revolution of the region bounded by {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=R-\frac{R}{h}x</math>{{nowrap end}} and the lines {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=0</math>{{nowrap end}} around the <math>x</math>-axis.|answer={{noprint|<math>\frac{\pi R^2 h}{3}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=2. Calculate the volume of the solid of revolution generated by revolving the region bounded by the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=x^2</math>{{nowrap end}} and the lines {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=1</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}} around the <math>x</math>-axis.|answer={{noprint|<math>\frac{\pi}{5}</math>}}}} {{noprint|[[Calculus/Volume_of_solids_of_revolution/Solutions|Solutions]]}}
==Washer Method== [[Image:Generating fxs washer method.svg|thumb|401px|right|Figure 3: A solid of revolution containing an irregularly shaped hole through its center is generated by revolving this region around the x-axis.]] [[Image:Approx generating fxs washer method.svg|thumb|401px|right|Figure 4: Approximation to the generating region in Figure 3.]]
The washer method is an extension of the disk method to solids of revolution formed by revolving an area bounded between two curves around the <math>x</math>-axis. Consider the solid of revolution formed by revolving the region in [[:File:Generating fxs washer method.svg|figure 3]] around the <math>x</math>-axis. The curve <math>f(x)</math> is the same as that in [[:File:Generating fx disk method.svg|figure 1]], but now our solid has an irregularly shaped hole through its center whose volume is that of the solid formed by revolving the curve <math>g(x)</math> around the <math>x</math>-axis. Our approximating region has the same upper boundary, <math>f_{step}(x)</math> as in [[:File:Approx generating fx disk method.svg|figure 2]], but now we extend only down to <math>g_{step}(x)</math> rather than all the way down to the <math>x</math>-axis. Revolving each block around the <math>x</math>-axis forms a washer-shaped solid with outer radius <math>f_{step}(x)</math> and inner radius <math>g_{step}(x)</math>. The volume of the <math>k</math>-th hollow cylinder is :<math>\begin{align}V_k&=\pi f(x_k)^2\Delta x-\pi g(x_k)^2\Delta x\\ &=\pi(f(x_k)^2-g(x_k)^2)\Delta x\end{align}</math> where {{nowrap begin}}<math>\Delta x=\frac{b-a}{n}</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>x_k=k\Delta x</math>{{nowrap end}}. The volume of the entire approximating solid is :<math>V_{approx}=\sum_{k=1}^n \pi(f(x_k)^2-g(x_k)^2)\Delta x</math> Taking the limit as <math>n</math> approaches infinity gives the volume :<math>\begin{align}V&=\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^n \pi(f(x_k)^2-g(x_k)^2)\Delta x\\ &=\int_a^b \pi(f(x)^2-g(x)^2)dx\end{align}</math>
===Exercises=== {{question-answer|question=3. Use the washer method to find the volume of a cone containing a central hole formed by revolving the region bounded by {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=R-\frac{R}{h}x</math>{{nowrap end}} and the lines {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=r</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=0</math>{{nowrap end}} around the <math>x</math>-axis.|answer={{noprint|<math>\pi h\left(\frac{R^2}{3}-r^2\right)</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=4. Calculate the volume of the solid of revolution generated by revolving the region bounded by the curves {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=x^2</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=x^3</math>{{nowrap end}} and the lines {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=1</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}} around the <math>x</math>-axis.|answer={{noprint|<math>\frac{2\pi}{35}</math>}}}} {{noprint|[[Calculus/Volume_of_solids_of_revolution/Solutions|Solutions]]}}
==Shell Method== [[Image:Generating fx shell method.svg|thumb|401px|right|Figure 5: A solid of revolution is generated by revolving this region around the y-axis.]] [[Image:Approx generating fx shell method.svg|thumb|401px|right|Figure 6: Approximation to the generating region in Figure 5.]] The shell method is another technique for finding the volume of a solid of revolution. Using this method sometimes makes it easier to set up and evaluate the integral. Consider the solid of revolution formed by revolving the region in [[:File:Generating fx shell method.svg|figure 5]] around the <math>y</math>-axis. While the generating region is the same as in [[:File:Generating fx disk method.svg|figure 1]], the axis of revolution has changed, making the disk method impractical for this problem. However, dividing the region up as we did previously suggests a similar method of finding the volume, only this time instead of adding up the volume of many approximating disks, we will add up the volume of many cylindrical shells. Consider the solid formed by revolving the region in [[:File:Approx generating fx shell method.svg|figure 6]] around the <math>y</math>-axis. The <math>k</math>-th rectangle sweeps out a hollow cylinder with height <math>\left|f(x_k)\right|</math> and with inner radius <math>x_k</math> and outer radius <math>x_k+\Delta x</math>, where {{nowrap begin}}<math>\Delta x=\frac{b-a}{n}</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>x_k=k\Delta x</math>{{nowrap end}}, the volume of which is :<math>\begin{align}V_k&=\pi((x_k+\Delta x)^2-x_k^2)|f(x_k)|\\ &=\pi((x_k^2+2x_k\Delta x+\Delta x^2)-x_k^2)|f(x_k)|\\ &=\pi(2x_k\Delta x+\Delta x^2)|f(x_k)|\end{align}</math> The volume of the entire approximating solid is :<math>V_{approx}=\sum_{k=1}^n \pi(2x_k\Delta x+\Delta x^2)|f(x_k)|</math> Taking the limit as <math>n</math> approaches infinity gives us the exact volume :<math>\begin{align}V&=\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^n \pi(2x_k\Delta x+\Delta x^2)|f(x_k)|\\ &=\pi\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\sum_{k=1}^n 2x_k\Delta x|f(x_k)|+\sum_{k=1}^n \Delta x^2|f(x_k)|\right)\end{align}</math> Since {{nowrap begin}}<math>|f|</math>{{nowrap end}} is continuous on {{nowrap begin}}<math>[a,b]</math>{{nowrap end}}, the [[Calculus/Some_Important_Theorems#Extreme_Value_Theorem|Extreme Value Theorem]] implies that {{nowrap begin}}<math>|f|</math>{{nowrap end}} has some maximum, <math>M</math>, on {{nowrap begin}}<math>[a,b]</math>{{nowrap end}}. Using this and the fact that {{nowrap begin}}<math>\Delta x^2|f(x_k)|>0</math>{{nowrap end}}, we have :<math>\sum_{k=1}^n 2x_k\Delta x|f(x_k)| \leq \sum_{k=1}^n 2x_k\Delta x|f(x_k)|+\sum_{k=1}^n \Delta x^2|f(x_k)| \leq \sum_{k=1}^n 2x_k\Delta x|f(x_k)|+\sum_{k=1}^n \Delta x^2 M</math> But :<math>\begin{align}\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^n \Delta x^2 M &= \lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^n \left(\frac{b-a}{n}\right)^2 M\\ &=\lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{(b-a)^2}{n} M\\ &=0\end{align}</math> So by the [[Calculus/Limits/An_Introduction_to_Limits#The_Squeeze_Theorem|Squeeze Theorem]] :<math>\pi\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\sum_{k=1}^n 2x_k\Delta x|f(x_k)|+\sum_{k=1}^n \Delta x^2|f(x_k)|\right) = \pi\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^n 2x_k\Delta x|f(x_k)|</math> , which is just the integral :<math>\int_a^b 2\pi x|f(x)|dx</math>
===Exercises=== {{question-answer|question=5. Find the volume of a cone with radius <math>R</math> and height <math>h</math> by using the shell method on the appropriate region which, when rotated around the <math>y</math>-axis, produces a cone with the given characteristics.|answer={{noprint|<math>\frac{\pi r^2 h}{3}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=6. Calculate the volume of the solid of revolution generated by revolving the region bounded by the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=x^2</math>{{nowrap end}} and the lines {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=1</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=0</math>{{nowrap end}} around the <math>y</math>-axis.|answer={{noprint|<math>\frac{\pi}{2}</math>}}}} {{noprint|[[Calculus/Volume_of_solids_of_revolution/Solutions|Solutions]]}}
